## Remarks  
 <span data-ttu-id="fa7ee-130">Há uma conversão implícita de cadeia de caracteres para <xref:System.Xml.Linq.XName>.</span><span class="sxs-lookup"><span data-stu-id="fa7ee-130">There is an implicit conversion from string to <xref:System.Xml.Linq.XName>.</span></span> <span data-ttu-id="fa7ee-131">Um uso comum desse construtor é para especificar uma cadeia de caracteres como o primeiro parâmetro em vez de criar um novo <xref:System.Xml.Linq.XName>, da seguinte maneira:</span><span class="sxs-lookup"><span data-stu-id="fa7ee-131">Typical use of this constructor is to specify a string as the first parameter instead of creating a new <xref:System.Xml.Linq.XName>, as follows:</span></span>  
  
```csharp  
XElement root = new XElement("Root",  
    new XAttribute("AnAttributeName", "Content")  
);  
```  
  
 <span data-ttu-id="fa7ee-132">Você também pode usar a sobrecarga de operador de adição com um <xref:System.Xml.Linq.XNamespace> e uma cadeia de caracteres para criar um <xref:System.Xml.Linq.XName>, da seguinte maneira:</span><span class="sxs-lookup"><span data-stu-id="fa7ee-132">You can also use the addition operator overload with an <xref:System.Xml.Linq.XNamespace> and a string to create an <xref:System.Xml.Linq.XName>, as follows:</span></span>  
  
```csharp  
XNamespace aw = "http://www.adventure-works.com";  
XElement root = new XElement(aw + "Root",  
    new XAttribute(aw + "AnAttributeName", "Content")  
);  
```  
  
 <span data-ttu-id="fa7ee-133">Para obter mais informações, consulte [trabalhando com Namespaces XML](http://msdn.microsoft.com/library/e3003209-3234-45be-a832-47feb7927430).</span><span class="sxs-lookup"><span data-stu-id="fa7ee-133">For more information, see [Working with XML Namespaces](http://msdn.microsoft.com/library/e3003209-3234-45be-a832-47feb7927430).</span></span>  
  
 <span data-ttu-id="fa7ee-134">Essas mesmas abordagens funcionará para o Visual Basic, no entanto, literais XML fornecem uma abordagem melhor para criar árvores XML.</span><span class="sxs-lookup"><span data-stu-id="fa7ee-134">These same approaches will work for Visual Basic, however XML literals provide a better approach for creating XML trees.</span></span>  
  
 <span data-ttu-id="fa7ee-135">O `value` parâmetro pode ser um <xref:System.String>, `double`, `float`, `decimal`, `bool`, <xref:System.DateTime>, ou <xref:System.TimeSpan>.</span><span class="sxs-lookup"><span data-stu-id="fa7ee-135">The `value` parameter can be a <xref:System.String>, `double`, `float`, `decimal`, `bool`, <xref:System.DateTime>, or <xref:System.TimeSpan>.</span></span> <span data-ttu-id="fa7ee-136">Se o valor for um <xref:System.DateTime> ou <xref:System.TimeSpan>, o valor do atributo está formatado corretamente, conforme as especificações do W3C.</span><span class="sxs-lookup"><span data-stu-id="fa7ee-136">If the value is a <xref:System.DateTime> or <xref:System.TimeSpan>, the value of the attribute is formatted correctly per the W3C specifications.</span></span>  
  
   
  
## Examples  
 <span data-ttu-id="fa7ee-137">O exemplo a seguir usa o construtor para criar atributos.</span><span class="sxs-lookup"><span data-stu-id="fa7ee-137">The following example uses this constructor to create attributes.</span></span> <span data-ttu-id="fa7ee-138">Ele passa cadeias de caracteres como o primeiro argumento para o <xref:System.Xml.Linq.XAttribute> construtor, que, em seguida, são implicitamente convertidos em <xref:System.Xml.Linq.XName> objetos.</span><span class="sxs-lookup"><span data-stu-id="fa7ee-138">It passes strings as the first argument to the <xref:System.Xml.Linq.XAttribute> constructor, which are then implicitly converted to <xref:System.Xml.Linq.XName> objects.</span></span> <span data-ttu-id="fa7ee-139">Os atributos são adicionados a um elemento.</span><span class="sxs-lookup"><span data-stu-id="fa7ee-139">The attributes are added to an element.</span></span>  
  
```csharp  
XElement root;  
  
double dbl = 12.345;  
XAttribute[] attArray = {  
    new XAttribute("Att4", 1),  
    new XAttribute("Att5", 2),  
    new XAttribute("Att6", 3)  
};  
DateTime dt = new DateTime(2006, 10, 6, 12, 30, 00);  
  
// string content  
root = new XElement("Root",  
    new XAttribute("Att1", "Some text"),  
  
    // double content  
    new XAttribute("Att2", dbl),  
  
    // DateTime content  
    new XAttribute("Att3", dt),  
  
    // XAttribute array content  
    attArray  
);  
  
Console.WriteLine(root);  
```  
  
```vb  
Dim dbl As Double = 12.345  
Dim attArray As XAttribute() = { _  
    New XAttribute("Att4", 1), _  
    New XAttribute("Att5", 2), _  
    New XAttribute("Att6", 3) _  
}  
Dim dt As DateTime = New DateTime(2006, 10, 6, 12, 30, 0)  
Dim root As XElement = <Root Att1="Some text"  
                           Att2=<%= dbl %>  
                           Att3=<%= dt %>  
                           <%= attArray %>  
                       />  
Console.WriteLine(root)  
```  
  
 <span data-ttu-id="fa7ee-140">Este exemplo gera a seguinte saída:</span><span class="sxs-lookup"><span data-stu-id="fa7ee-140">This example produces the following output:</span></span>  
  
```  
  
<Root Att1="Some text" Att2="12.345" Att3="2006-10-06T12:30:00" Att4="1" Att5="2" Att6="3" />  
```

  
  
## Remarks  
 <span data-ttu-id="fa7ee-189">O espaço de valor de um atributo ou elemento que contém o conteúdo de data e hora está intimamente relacionado para as datas e horas descritas no ISO 8601.</span><span class="sxs-lookup"><span data-stu-id="fa7ee-189">The value space of an attribute or element that contains date and time content is closely related to the dates and times described in ISO 8601.</span></span> <span data-ttu-id="fa7ee-190">Ao criar um atributo ou elemento que contém o conteúdo de data e hora, os valores de atributo ou elemento são formatados por especificação W3C.</span><span class="sxs-lookup"><span data-stu-id="fa7ee-190">When creating an attribute or element that contains date and time content, the attribute or element values are formatted per the W3C specification.</span></span> <span data-ttu-id="fa7ee-191">Consulte a especificação do W3C para obter mais detalhes.</span><span class="sxs-lookup"><span data-stu-id="fa7ee-191">See the W3C specification for more details.</span></span>  
  
 <span data-ttu-id="fa7ee-192">Comportamento é incerto ao converter para um <xref:System.DateTime> de um atributo ou elemento.</span><span class="sxs-lookup"><span data-stu-id="fa7ee-192">Behavior is lax when casting to a <xref:System.DateTime> from an attribute or element.</span></span> <span data-ttu-id="fa7ee-193">Mesmo se o valor de atributo ou elemento não está formatado exatamente por especificação W3C, o valor é convertido corretamente em um <xref:System.DateTime>.</span><span class="sxs-lookup"><span data-stu-id="fa7ee-193">Even if the attribute or element value is not formatted exactly per the W3C specification, the value is appropriately converted to a <xref:System.DateTime>.</span></span>  
  
 <span data-ttu-id="fa7ee-194">Este operador de conversão usa <xref:System.Globalization.CultureInfo.InvariantCulture%2A?displayProperty=nameWithType> para converter de um <xref:System.DateTime>.</span><span class="sxs-lookup"><span data-stu-id="fa7ee-194">This conversion operator uses <xref:System.Globalization.CultureInfo.InvariantCulture%2A?displayProperty=nameWithType> to convert from a <xref:System.DateTime>.</span></span>  
 
## Examples  
 <span data-ttu-id="fa7ee-195">O exemplo a seguir cria um atributo com conteúdo de data e hora.</span><span class="sxs-lookup"><span data-stu-id="fa7ee-195">The following example creates an attribute with date and time content.</span></span> <span data-ttu-id="fa7ee-196">Em seguida, converte-o para <xref:System.DateTime> para recuperar o valor.</span><span class="sxs-lookup"><span data-stu-id="fa7ee-196">It then casts it to <xref:System.DateTime> to retrieve the value.</span></span>  
  
```csharp  
// Behavior is strict when formatting an XML element or attribute from a DateTime,  
// but behavior is lax when casting to a DateTime from an element or attribute.  
  
XElement root = new XElement("Root",  
    new XAttribute("Att", new DateTime(2006, 10, 6, 12, 30, 0))  
);  
Console.WriteLine(root);  
  
// casting from a strictly formatted XML attribute  
DateTime dt = (DateTime)root.Attribute("Att");  
Console.WriteLine("dt={0}", dt);  
Console.WriteLine("-----");  
  
// if root is formatted in some different way than the standard ISO 8601, if at all possible,  
// the value is appropriately converted to DateTime  
  
XAttribute dtAtt = new XAttribute("OrderDate", "October 6, 2006");  
Console.WriteLine(dtAtt);  
DateTime orderDate = (DateTime)dtAtt;  
Console.WriteLine("OrderDate={0:d}", orderDate);  
```  
  
```vb  
' Behavior is strict when formatting an XML element or attribute from a DateTime,  
' but behavior is lax when casting to a DateTime from an element or attribute.  
Dim root As XElement = <Root Att=<%= New DateTime(2006, 10, 6, 12, 30, 0) %>/>  
  
Console.WriteLine(root)  
  
' casting from a strictly formatted XML attribute  
Dim dt As DateTime = CType(root.Attribute("Att"), DateTime)  
Console.WriteLine("dt={0}", dt)  
Console.WriteLine("-----")  
  
' if root is formatted in some different way than the standard ISO 8601, if at all possible,  
' the value is appropriately converted to DateTime  
Dim dtAtt As XAttribute = New XAttribute("OrderDate", "October 6, 2006")  
Console.WriteLine(dtAtt)  
Dim orderDate As DateTime = CType(dtAtt, DateTime)  
Console.WriteLine("OrderDate={0:d}", orderDate)  
```  
  
 <span data-ttu-id="fa7ee-197">Este exemplo gera a seguinte saída:</span><span class="sxs-lookup"><span data-stu-id="fa7ee-197">This example produces the following output:</span></span>  
  
```  
<Root Att="2006-10-06T12:30:00" />  
dt=10/6/2006 12:30:00 PM  
-----  
OrderDate="October 6, 2006"  
OrderDate=10/6/2006  
```

  
  
## Remarks  
 <span data-ttu-id="fa7ee-433">Você pode usar essa propriedade para obter ou definir o valor de um atributo.</span><span class="sxs-lookup"><span data-stu-id="fa7ee-433">You can use this property to get or set the value of an attribute.</span></span>  
  
 <span data-ttu-id="fa7ee-434">Configuração para essa propriedade gerará o <xref:System.Xml.Linq.XObject.Changed> e <xref:System.Xml.Linq.XObject.Changing> eventos.</span><span class="sxs-lookup"><span data-stu-id="fa7ee-434">Setting this property will raise the <xref:System.Xml.Linq.XObject.Changed> and the <xref:System.Xml.Linq.XObject.Changing> events.</span></span>  
  
 <span data-ttu-id="fa7ee-435">Se você estiver obtendo o valor e o atributo pode não existir, ele é mais conveniente usar os operadores de conversão explícita e atribua o atributo para um tipo anulável como `string` ou <xref:System.Nullable%601> de <xref:System.Int32>.</span><span class="sxs-lookup"><span data-stu-id="fa7ee-435">If you are getting the value and the attribute might not exist, it is more convenient to use the explicit conversion operators, and assign the attribute to a nullable type such as `string` or <xref:System.Nullable%601> of <xref:System.Int32>.</span></span> <span data-ttu-id="fa7ee-436">Se o atributo não existe, o tipo anulável é definido como `null`.</span><span class="sxs-lookup"><span data-stu-id="fa7ee-436">If the attribute does not exist, then the nullable type is set to `null`.</span></span> <span data-ttu-id="fa7ee-437">Antes de usar essa propriedade, você deve garantir que o <xref:System.Xml.Linq.XElement.Attribute%2A> método não retorna `null`.</span><span class="sxs-lookup"><span data-stu-id="fa7ee-437">Before using this property, you must make sure that the <xref:System.Xml.Linq.XElement.Attribute%2A> method does not return `null`.</span></span>  
  
   
  
## Examples  
 <span data-ttu-id="fa7ee-438">O exemplo a seguir cria um elemento com um atributo.</span><span class="sxs-lookup"><span data-stu-id="fa7ee-438">The following example creates an element with an attribute.</span></span> <span data-ttu-id="fa7ee-439">Ele recupera o valor do atributo e define-lo.</span><span class="sxs-lookup"><span data-stu-id="fa7ee-439">It then retrieves the value of the attribute, and then sets it.</span></span>  
  
 <span data-ttu-id="fa7ee-440">Observe que o exemplo do Visual Basic usa a propriedade de atributo XML.</span><span class="sxs-lookup"><span data-stu-id="fa7ee-440">Note that the Visual Basic example uses the XML attribute property.</span></span>  
  
```csharp  
XElement root = new XElement("Root",  
    new XAttribute("Att", "content")  
);  
XAttribute att = root.FirstAttribute;  
Console.WriteLine(att.Value);  
att.Value = "new text";  
Console.WriteLine(att.Value);  
```  
  
```vb  
Dim root As XElement = <Root Att="content"/>  
Console.WriteLine(root.@Att)  
root.@Att = "new text"  
Console.WriteLine(root.@Att)  
```  
  
 <span data-ttu-id="fa7ee-441">Este exemplo gera a seguinte saída:</span><span class="sxs-lookup"><span data-stu-id="fa7ee-441">This example produces the following output:</span></span>  
  
```  
content  
new text  
```  
  
 <span data-ttu-id="fa7ee-442">O exemplo a seguir mostra o benefício de usar os operadores de conversão explícita para obter o valor de um atributo que pode não existir:</span><span class="sxs-lookup"><span data-stu-id="fa7ee-442">The following example shows the benefit of using the explicit conversion operators to get the value of an attribute that might not exist:</span></span>  
  
```csharp  
XElement root = new XElement("Root",  
    new XAttribute("Att1", "attribute 1 content"),  
    new XAttribute("Att2", "2")  
);  
  
// The following assignments demonstrate why it is easier to use  
// casting when the attribute might or might not exist.  
  
string c1 = (string)root.Attribute("Att1");  
Console.WriteLine("c1:{0}", c1 == null ? "attribute does not exist" : c1);  
  
int? c2 = (int?)root.Attribute("Att2");  
Console.WriteLine("c2:{0}", c2 == null ? "attribute does not exist" : c2.ToString());  
  
string c3 = (string)root.Attribute("Att3");  
Console.WriteLine("c3:{0}", c3 == null ? "attribute does not exist" : c3);  
  
int? c4 = (int?)root.Attribute("Att4");  
Console.WriteLine("c4:{0}", c4 == null ? "attribute does not exist" : c4.ToString());  
  
Console.WriteLine();  
  
// The following assignments show the necessary code when using  
// the value property when the attribute might or might not exist.  
  
XAttribute att1 = root.Attribute("Att1");  
string v1;  
if (att1 == null)  
    v1 = null;  
else  
    v1 = att1.Value;  
Console.WriteLine("v1:{0}", v1 == null ? "attribute does not exist" : v1);  
  
XAttribute att2 = root.Attribute("Att2");  
int? v2;  
if (att2 == null)  
    v2 = null;  
else  
    v2 = Int32.Parse(att2.Value);  
Console.WriteLine("v2:{0}", v2 == null ? "attribute does not exist" : v2.ToString());  
  
XAttribute att3 = root.Attribute("Att3");  
string v3;  
if (att3 == null)  
    v3 = null;  
else  
    v3 = att3.Value;  
Console.WriteLine("v3:{0}", v3 == null ? "attribute does not exist" : v3);  
  
XAttribute att4 = root.Attribute("Att4");  
int? v4;  
if (att4 == null)  
    v4 = null;  
else  
    v4 = Int32.Parse(att4.Value);  
Console.WriteLine("v4:{0}", v4 == null ? "attribute does not exist" : v4.ToString());  
```  
  
```vb  
Dim root As XElement = <Root Att1="attribute 1 content" Att2="2"/>  
  
' The following assignments demonstrate why it is easier to use  
' casting when the attribute might or might not exist.  
  
Dim c1 As String = CStr(root.Attribute("Att1"))  
Console.WriteLine("c1:{0}", IIf(c1 Is Nothing, "attribute does not exist", c1))  
  
Dim c2 As Nullable(Of Integer) = CType(root.Attribute("Att2"), Nullable(Of Integer))  
Console.WriteLine("c2:{0}", IIf(c2.HasValue, c2, "attribute does not exist"))  
  
Dim c3 As String = CStr(root.Attribute("Att3"))  
Console.WriteLine("c3:{0}", IIf(c3 Is Nothing, "attribute does not exist", c3))  
  
Dim c4 As Nullable(Of Integer) = CType(root.Attribute("Att4"), Nullable(Of Integer))  
Console.WriteLine("c4:{0}", IIf(c4.HasValue, c4, "attribute does not exist"))  
  
Console.WriteLine()  
  
' The following assignments show the necessary code when using  
' the value property when the attribute might or might not exist.  
  
Dim att1 As XAttribute = root.Attribute("Att1")  
Dim v1 As String  
If att1 Is Nothing Then  
    v1 = Nothing  
Else  
    v1 = att1.Value  
End If  
  
Console.WriteLine("v1:{0}", IIf(v1 Is Nothing, "attribute does not exist", v1))  
  
Dim att2 As XAttribute = root.Attribute("Att2")  
Dim v2 As Nullable(Of Integer)  
If att2 Is Nothing Then  
    v2 = Nothing  
Else  
    v2 = Int32.Parse(att2.Value)  
End If  
  
Console.WriteLine("v2:{0}", IIf(v2.HasValue, v2, "attribute does not exist"))  
  
Dim att3 As XAttribute = root.Attribute("Att3")  
Dim v3 As String  
If att3 Is Nothing Then  
    v3 = Nothing  
Else  
    v3 = att3.Value  
End If  
  
Console.WriteLine("v3:{0}", IIf(v3 Is Nothing, "attribute does not exist", v3))  
  
Dim att4 As XAttribute = root.Attribute("Att4")  
Dim v4 As Nullable(Of Integer)  
If att4 Is Nothing Then  
    v4 = Nothing  
Else  
    v4 = Int32.Parse(att4.Value)  
End If  
  
Console.WriteLine("v4:{0}", IIf(v4.HasValue, v4, "attribute does not exist"))  
```  
  
